=Box Office: 'Hobbit: Desolation of Smaug' Wins Weekend With $73.7 Million in Domestic Debut|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=20 December 2013|first=Rebecca|last=Ford|date=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''The Hobbit: The Battle of the Five Armies''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 60%<ref name=\"rotreturn\">{{cite web |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_hobbit_there_and_back_again/ |title=The Battle of the Five Armies reviews|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 59<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-hobbit-there-and-back-again |title=The Battle of the Five Armies reviews | publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| A-<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-hobbit-five-armies-757340|title=Box Office: 'Hobbit: Five Armies' Crushes 'Museum,' 'Annie' With $90.6M|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=23 December 2014|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|date=21 December 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Middle-earth (film franchise)}}\n* [[Adaptations of The Lord of the Rings]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Middle-earth films}}\n{{The Lord of the Rings & The Hobbit film series}}\n{{Middle-earth}}\n\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 1977]]\n[[Category:Adaptations of works by J. R. R. Tolkien|Films]]\n[[Category:Middle-earth films| ]]\n", "name_user": "Chen Geller", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth_in_film"}
{"title_page": "Hyam Greenbaum", "text_new": "[[File:Radiolympia.jpg|thumb|Hyam Greenbaum and the BBC Television Orchestra in a test broadcast from [[Alexandra Palace television station]] to audiences at Radiolympia]]\n\n'''Hyam Greenbaum''' (12 May 1901 \u2013 13 May 1942) was an English conductor, violinist and composer who in 1936 became the world's first conductor of a television orchestra.<ref name=tv>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1479086/Sidonie-Goossens.html Obituary, Sidonie Goossens, ''Daily Telegraph'', 16 December, 2004] </ref> He was friendly with many of his English music contemporaries, including [[Constant Lambert]], [[Alan Rawsthorne]], and [[William Walton]] and often helped them with technical advice on orchestration.<ref name=hughes>[[Spike Hughes]], ''Opening Bars'' (1946) p 354-5</ref> His sister was the pianist and composer [[Kyla Greenbaum]] (1922-2017).\n\n== Career ==\nAs a child Greenbaum was taught violin by his mother and piano by his father (Solomon Greenbaum, a tailor of Polish origins)<ref>Marston, John: ''Sidonie Goossens'', in the Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, 2009</ref> before studying at the Brighton School of Music and the [[Royal College of Music]].<ref name=pal>[https://books.google.it/books?id=_T_HCg17ufIC&pg=PA371&lpg=PA371&dq=%22Greenbaum%22+%22Bumps%22+%22composition%22&source=bl&ots=ZxN06yfBra&sig=ACfU3U0dGNwk7c8aOsQ8WtOMrga-R-A0zQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiXhYf7vsLlAhXpAhAIHXU2AeIQ6AEwAnoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Greenbaum%22&f=false Rubenstein, W. (ed.) ''The Palgrave Dictionary of Anglo-Jewish History'' (2011)]</ref>\nAlthough he had ambitions to become a conductor from the start, Greenbaum began his musical career in 1916 leading the second violins in the Queen's Hall Orchestra,<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/8f99da4c1426492f902e1f44040817ee ''Radio Times'', Issue 894, 28 February 1939, p 24]</ref> and from 1923 until 1936 played second violin and piano for the [[Sergei Diaghilev|Diaghilev Ballet]].<ref name=pal/> In 1924 he joined the [[Antonio Brosa|Brosa String Quartet]] playing second violin. From 1930 until 1934 he was a music director for [[Charles B. Cochran|C. B. Cochran]] on London productions such as [[Jerome Kern]]'s ''[[The Cat and the Fiddle (musical)|The Cat and the Fiddle]]'' (March 1932, 219 performances), Kern's ''[[Music in the Air]]'' (May 1933, 275 performances) and [[Cole Porter]]'s ''[[Nymph Errant]]'' (October 1933, 154 performances)<ref>[http://www.overthefootlights.co.uk/London%20Musicals%201930-1934.pub.pdf ''London Musicals, 1930-34'']</ref>. In the early 1930s he also joined [[Decca Records|Decca]] as a recording manager.<ref name=rio>[https://books.google.it/books?id=hMzCAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA302&lpg=PA302&dq=%22Greenbaum%22+%22Bumps%22+%22composition%22&source=bl&ots=K74dXaV_I0&sig=ACfU3U04anoML5z107ONUuDh1hVH2KpWGg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiXhYf7vsLlAhXpAhAIHXU2AeIQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Greenbaum%22%20%22Bumps%22%20%22composition%22&f=false Lloyd, Stephen. ''Constant Lanbert: Beyond The Rio Grande''] (2015)</ref>\n\nIn 1936 Greenbaum founded the [[BBC Television Orchestra]], which played on the inaugural programme broadcast when regular British television broadcasts commenced on 26 August 1936 to an estimated 123,000 viewers.<ref name=tv/> This was the first high-definition standard ([[405-line television system|405 lines]]) television test transmission, with the orchestra broadcasting from [[Alexandra Palace]] to the [[Radiolympia]] exhibition being held at [[Olympia London]].<ref name=\"TH\">{{cite web |title=The History of the BBC: The first TV era|url=http://www.televisionheaven.co.uk/history_of_the_bbc_1.htm |publisher=Television Heaven |accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=History of the BBC - The Story of the BBC - Television As We Know It|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/historyofthebbc/research/general/tvstory6|website=BBC|publisher=BBC|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> The orchestra also played on the opening day of BBC Television [[High-definition television|high-definition]] broadcast on 2 November 1936.<ref>[http://www.teletronic.co.uk/tvera.htm The History of the BBC]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btinternet.com/~roger.beckwith/bh/odds/tvru.htm |title=BBC liner notes, 1936 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421231846/http://www.btinternet.com/~roger.beckwith/bh/odds/tvru.htm |archivedate=21 April 2008 }}</ref> Its repertoire was wide, ranging from music for drama productions through to a televised adaptation of ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' (in two one-hour sections) on 24 January 1938.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/895130c4e7344c0290d12446d9717b85 ''Radio Tines'', Issue 747, 23 January 1938, p 16]</ref>  Greenbaum, with a group of others at the BBC (including Stephen Thomas, [[Dallas Bower]], [[Desmond Davis]] and members of the British Music Drama Opera Company), presented 29 operas on television between 1936 and 1939.<ref>[https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-0000041850 Salter, Lionel and others: 'Television' in ''Grove Music Online'']</ref>\n\nThe orchestra was disbanded in September 1939 at the outbreak of World War II when the BBC's television service was suspended, after which Greenbaum used a nucleus of its players to form the [[BBC Radio Orchestra|BBC Revue Orchestra]], playing light variety music for BBC radio from its base in [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]], North Wales.<ref name=rio/> However, he continued to conduct a wide range of repertoire for the BBC with other orchestras. For instance, on 19 November 1941 he conducted [[Franz Liszt]]'s symphonic poem ''Orpheus'' and [[Ferruccio Busoni]]'s Violin Concerto.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/c3148314874f42faa6f015c002e2c951 ''Radio Times'' Issue 946, 16 November 1941, p 14]</ref>\n\n== Composition and orchestration ==\nGreenbaum was a member of the \"Warlock Gang\", followers of composer and music critic [[Peter Warlock]] (Philip Heseltine).<ref name=foss>[https://boydellandbrewer.com/i-music-in-their-time-i-the-memoirs-and-letters-of-dora-and-hubert-foss-hb.html Lloyd, Stephen (ed.). ''Music in Their Time: The Memoirs and Letters of Dora and Hubert Foss''] (2019)</ref> Others were [[Cecil Gray (composer)|Cecil Gray]], [[Ernest John Moeran|E. J. Moeran]], Constant Lambert and [[Leslie Heward]]. It has been suggested that Heseltine's influence led to Greenbaum's heavy drinking habit. In the late 1920s and early 1930s, the London home of Hyam Greenbaum and his wife, the harpist [[Sidonie Goossens]], became a regular meeting place for an expanded circle of hard-drinking musicians, also including [[Arnold Bax]], [[Patrick Hadley]], [[Spike Hughes]], Alan Rawsthorne and William Walton. During the war they moved to Bristol, living with Rawsthorne and his wife Jessie Hinchcliffe at the Clifton Arts Club.<ref>'[http://www.musicweb-international.com/rawsth/THE%20CREEL_VOL8_No2.pdf ''The Creel'', Vol 8 No 2 (2016) p 3]</ref> This was bombed in November 1940, and many of Rawsthorne\u2019s manuscripts were destroyed.\n\nAs a composer, Greenbaum achieved some recognition with his ''Parfums de Nuits'' for oboe and orchestra.<ref>[http://www.musicweb-international.com/garlands/241.htm Philip Scowcroft, Musicweb International]</ref> which was performed at the [[Proms]] on 12 October 1922.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/egq38g BBC Proms performance archive]</ref>  He then conducted the premiere of his orchestral piece ''A Sea Poem'' at the 1923 Proms, repeating it the following year.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/eqq38g BBC Proms performance archive]</ref> However, his greatest contributions to contemporary music came from his conducting and orchestration work, and from helping other composers at difficult times in the composition process. He orchestrated some of William Walton's film scores, including [[Escape Me Never (1935 film)|''Escape Me Never'']] in 1935 and [[As You Like It (1936 film)|''As You Like It'']] in 1936<ref>[https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803095906257 Oxford Reference]</ref> and assisted Walton with both the [[Viola Concerto (Walton)|Viola Concerto]] and the [[Symphony No. 1 (Walton)|Symphony No 1]].<ref>[https://books.google.it/books?id=wWfNcDTDtCEC&pg=PA112&lpg=PA112&dq=%22Greenbaum%22+%22Bumps%22+%22composition%22&source=bl&ots=wVtMawHAyz&sig=ACfU3U0CUUEOl7OTAu_fupIbWFOqPWg3ag&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiXhYf7vsLlAhXpAhAIHXU2AeIQ6AEwAHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Greenbaum%22&f=false Lloyd, Stephen. ''William Walton, Muse of Fire'' (2001), p 112]</ref><ref>Gray, Cecil: ''Hyam Greenbaum (1901-42)'', The Music Review 3(3), August 1942, p 221-222</ref> Similarly, he helped Constant Lambert complete his choral work ''[[Summer's Last Will and Testament (Lambert)|Summer's Last Will and Testament]]'', also standing in as conductor for the second performance when Lambert was too ill to appear himself.<ref name=rio/>\n\nGeenbaum married Sidonie Goossens in 1924. He died of alcohol-related problems, one day after his 41st birthday, following the death of their only son at birth.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/sidonie-goossens-25032.html Sidonie Goossens obituary, ''The Independent'', 16 December, 2004]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.bbc.com/historyofthebbc/100-voices/birth-of-tv/opening-night BBC: Opening Night, November, 1936]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0338460/ Hyam Greenbaum at IMDB]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Greenbaum, Hyam}}\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:English conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:British male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:English composers]]\n[[Category:English violinists]]\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Radiolympia.jpg|thumb|Hyam Greenbaum and the BBC Television Orchestra in a test broadcast from [[Alexandra Palace television station]] to audiences at Radiolympia]]\n\n'''Hyam Greenbaum''' (12 May 1901 \u2013 13 May 1942) was an English conductor, violinist and composer who in 1936 became the world's first conductor of a television orchestra.<ref name=tv>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1479086/Sidonie-Goossens.html Obituary, Sidonie Goossens, ''Daily Telegraph'', 16 December, 2004] </ref> He was friendly with many of his English music contemporaries, including [[Constant Lambert]], [[Alan Rawsthorne]], and [[William Walton]] and often helped them with technical advice on orchestration.<ref name=hughes>[[Spike Hughes]], ''Opening Bars'' (1946) p 354-5</ref> His sister was the pianist and composer [[Kyla Greenbaum]] (1922-2017).\n\n== Career ==\nAs a child Greenbaum was taught violin by his mother and piano by his father (Solomon Greenbaum, a tailor of Polish origins)<ref>Marston, John: ''Sidonie Goossens'', in the Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, 2009</ref> before studying at the Brighton School of Music and the [[Royal College of Music]].<ref name=pal>[https://books.google.it/books?id=_T_HCg17ufIC&pg=PA371&lpg=PA371&dq=%22Greenbaum%22+%22Bumps%22+%22composition%22&source=bl&ots=ZxN06yfBra&sig=ACfU3U0dGNwk7c8aOsQ8WtOMrga-R-A0zQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiXhYf7vsLlAhXpAhAIHXU2AeIQ6AEwAnoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Greenbaum%22&f=false Rubenstein, W. (ed.) ''The Palgrave Dictionary of Anglo-Jewish History'' (2011)]</ref>\nAlthough he had ambitions to become a conductor from the start, Greenbaum began his musical career in 1916 leading the second violins in the Queen's Hall Orchestra,<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/8f99da4c1426492f902e1f44040817ee ''Radio Times'', Issue 894, 28 February 1939, p 24]</ref> and from 1923 until 1936 played second violin and piano for the [[Sergei Diaghilev|Diaghilev Ballet]].<ref name=pal/> In 1924 he joined the [[Antonio Brosa|Brosa String Quartet]] playing second violin. From 1930 until 1934 he was a music director for [[Charles B. Cochran|C. B. Cochran]] on London productions such as [[Jerome Kern]]'s ''[[The Cat and the Fiddle (musical)|The Cat and the Fiddle]]'' (March 1932, 219 performances), Kern's ''[[Music in the Air]]'' (May 1933, 275 performances) and [[Cole Porter]]'s ''[[Nymph Errant]]'' (October 1933, 154 performances)<ref>[http://www.overthefootlights.co.uk/London%20Musicals%201930-1934.pub.pdf ''London Musicals, 1930-34'']</ref>. In the early 1930s he also joined [[Decca Records|Decca]] as a recording manager.<ref name=rio>[https://books.google.it/books?id=hMzCAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA302&lpg=PA302&dq=%22Greenbaum%22+%22Bumps%22+%22composition%22&source=bl&ots=K74dXaV_I0&sig=ACfU3U04anoML5z107ONUuDh1hVH2KpWGg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiXhYf7vsLlAhXpAhAIHXU2AeIQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Greenbaum%22%20%22Bumps%22%20%22composition%22&f=false Lloyd, Stephen. ''Constant Lanbert: Beyond The Rio Grande''] (2015)</ref>\n\nIn 1936 Greenbaum founded the [[BBC Television Orchestra]], which played on the inaugural programme broadcast when regular British television broadcasts commenced on 26 August 1936 to an estimated 123,000 viewers.<ref name=tv/> This was the first high-definition standard ([[405-line television system|405 lines]]) television test transmission, with the orchestra broadcasting from [[Alexandra Palace]] to the [[Radiolympia]] exhibition being held at [[Olympia London]].<ref name=\"TH\">{{cite web |title=The History of the BBC: The first TV era|url=http://www.televisionheaven.co.uk/history_of_the_bbc_1.htm |publisher=Television Heaven |accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=History of the BBC - The Story of the BBC - Television As We Know It|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/historyofthebbc/research/general/tvstory6|website=BBC|publisher=BBC|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> The orchestra also played on the opening day of BBC Television [[High-definition television|high-definition]] broadcast on 2 November 1936.<ref>[http://www.teletronic.co.uk/tvera.htm The History of the BBC]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btinternet.com/~roger.beckwith/bh/odds/tvru.htm |title=BBC liner notes, 1936 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421231846/http://www.btinternet.com/~roger.beckwith/bh/odds/tvru.htm |archivedate=21 April 2008 }}</ref> Its repertoire was wide, ranging from music for drama productions through to a televised adaptation of ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' (in two one-hour sections) on 24 January 1938.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/895130c4e7344c0290d12446d9717b85 ''Radio Tines'', Issue 747, 23 January 1938, p 16]</ref> \n\nThe orchestra was disbanded in September 1939 at the outbreak of World War II when the BBC's television service was suspended, after which Greenbaum used a nucleus of its players to form the [[BBC Radio Orchestra|BBC Revue Orchestra]], playing light variety music for BBC radio from its base in [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]], North Wales.<ref name=rio/> However, he continued to conduct a wide range of repertoire for the BBC with other orchestras. For instance, on 19 November 1941 he conducted [[Franz Liszt]]'s symphonic poem ''Orpheus'' and [[Ferruccio Busoni]]'s Violin Concerto.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/c3148314874f42faa6f015c002e2c951 ''Radio Times'' Issue 946, 16 November 1941, p 14]</ref>\n\n== Composition and orchestration ==\nGreenbaum was a member of the \"Warlock Gang\", followers of composer and music critic [[Peter Warlock]] (Philip Heseltine).<ref name=foss>[https://boydellandbrewer.com/i-music-in-their-time-i-the-memoirs-and-letters-of-dora-and-hubert-foss-hb.html Lloyd, Stephen (ed.). ''Music in Their Time: The Memoirs and Letters of Dora and Hubert Foss''] (2019)</ref> Others were [[Cecil Gray (composer)|Cecil Gray]], [[Ernest John Moeran|E. J. Moeran]], Constant Lambert and [[Leslie Heward]]. It has been suggested that Heseltine's influence led to Greenbaum's heavy drinking habit. In the late 1920s and early 1930s, the London home of Hyam Greenbaum and his wife, the harpist [[Sidonie Goossens]], became a regular meeting place for an expanded circle of hard-drinking musicians, also including [[Arnold Bax]], [[Patrick Hadley]], [[Spike Hughes]], Alan Rawsthorne and William Walton. During the war they moved to Bristol, living with Rawsthorne and his wife Jessie Hinchcliffe at the Clifton Arts Club.<ref>'[http://www.musicweb-international.com/rawsth/THE%20CREEL_VOL8_No2.pdf ''The Creel'', Vol 8 No 2 (2016) p 3]</ref> This was bombed in November 1940, and many of Rawsthorne\u2019s manuscripts were destroyed.\n\nAs a composer, Greenbaum achieved some recognition with his ''Parfums de Nuits'' for oboe and orchestra.<ref>[http://www.musicweb-international.com/garlands/241.htm Philip Scowcroft, Musicweb International]</ref> which was performed at the [[Proms]] on 12 October 1922.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/egq38g BBC Proms performance archive]</ref>  He then conducted the premiere of his orchestral piece ''A Sea Poem'' at the 1923 Proms, repeating it the following year.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/eqq38g BBC Proms performance archive]</ref> However, his greatest contributions to contemporary music came from his conducting and orchestration work, and from helping other composers at difficult times in the composition process. He orchestrated some of William Walton's film scores, including [[Escape Me Never (1935 film)|''Escape Me Never'']] in 1935 and [[As You Like It (1936 film)|''As You Like It'']] in 1936<ref>[https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803095906257 Oxford Reference]</ref> and assisted Walton with both the [[Viola Concerto (Walton)|Viola Concerto]] and the [[Symphony No. 1 (Walton)|Symphony No 1]].<ref>[https://books.google.it/books?id=wWfNcDTDtCEC&pg=PA112&lpg=PA112&dq=%22Greenbaum%22+%22Bumps%22+%22composition%22&source=bl&ots=wVtMawHAyz&sig=ACfU3U0CUUEOl7OTAu_fupIbWFOqPWg3ag&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiXhYf7vsLlAhXpAhAIHXU2AeIQ6AEwAHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Greenbaum%22&f=false Lloyd, Stephen. ''William Walton, Muse of Fire'' (2001), p 112]</ref><ref>Gray, Cecil: ''Hyam Greenbaum (1901-42)'', The Music Review 3(3), August 1942, p 221-222</ref> Similarly, he helped Constant Lambert complete his choral work ''[[Summer's Last Will and Testament (Lambert)|Summer's Last Will and Testament]]'', also standing in as conductor for the second performance when Lambert was too ill to appear himself.<ref name=rio/>\n\nGeenbaum married Sidonie Goossens in 1924. He died of alcohol-related problems, one day after his 41st birthday, following the death of their only son at birth.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/sidonie-goossens-25032.html Sidonie Goossens obituary, ''The Independent'', 16 December, 2004]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.bbc.com/historyofthebbc/100-voices/birth-of-tv/opening-night BBC: Opening Night, November, 1936]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0338460/ Hyam Greenbaum at IMDB]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Greenbaum, Hyam}}\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:English conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:British male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:English composers]]\n[[Category:English violinists]]\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Sfjohna", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyam_Greenbaum"}
